This paper is likely to belong to the arXiv CS sub-category of natural language processing (cs.CL) because it presents an atlas of everyday commonsense reasoning organized through textual descriptions of inferential knowledge. It also proposes a generative training approach for neural models to acquire simple commonsense capabilities and reason about previously unseen events. Additionally, it could belong to the sub-category of artificial intelligence (cs.AI) because it focuses on inferential knowledge and proposes a multitask learning approach for more accurate inference. It could also belong to the sub-category of machine learning (cs.LG) because it proposes a generative training approach for neural models. Furthermore, it could belong to the sub-category of computational complexity (cs.CC) because it proposes a hierarchical structure of if-then relation types for more accurate inference. Finally, it could belong to the sub-category of cryptography and security (cs.CR) because it proposes a human evaluation of the models' performance.
